Univariate Analysis¶

In [13]:
from sklearn.feature_selection import SelectKBest, f_classif

# Assuming X contains all numerical features and y is the target variable
X=numeric_features.iloc[:,0:9]
y=data.iloc[:,-1]
# Select top 5 features using univariate analysis (e.g., ANOVA F-value)
selector = SelectKBest(score_func=f_classif, k=7)
X_new = selector.fit_transform(X, y)

# Get the indices of the selected features
selected_indices = selector.get_support(indices=True)
selected_features_univariate = X.columns[selected_indices]

# Print the top 5 selected features
print("Top 7 features selected using univariate analysis:")
for i in selected_features_univariate:
    print(i)

RFE(Recursive Feature Elemination)¶

In [14]:
from sklearn.feature_selection import RFE
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression

# Assuming X contains all numerical features and y is the target variable

# Initialize the logistic regression model
model = LogisticRegression()

# Perform Recursive Feature Elimination (RFE) with cross-validation
selector = RFE(estimator=model, n_features_to_select=7, step=1)
selector.fit(X, y)

# Get the indices of the selected features
selected_indices_rfe = selector.support_
selected_features_rfe = X.columns[selected_indices_rfe]

# Print the top 7 selected features
print("Top 7 features selected using RFE:")
for i in selected_features_rfe:
    print(i)

Feature Importance¶

In [15]:
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier

# Assuming X contains all numerical features and y is the target variable

# Initialize the random forest classifier
model = RandomForestClassifier()

# Fit the model to obtain feature importances
model.fit(X, y)

# Get feature importances
feature_importances = model.feature_importances_

# Get indices of top 7 features based on importance
top_indices = feature_importances.argsort()[-7:][::-1]
selected_features_importance = X.columns[top_indices]

# Print the top 7 selected features
print("Top 7 features selected using feature importance:")
for i in selected_features_importance:
    print(i)

Interpretation of results¶

By combining the results from all these methods, we can identify the top numerical features that are most important
for predicting the target variable in the bank marketing campaign dataset.

In [16]:
# Assuming you have obtained selected_features_univariate, selected_features_rfe, selected_features_importance, and selected_features_scatterplot

# Convert feature lists to sets
set_univariate = set(selected_features_univariate)
set_rfe = set(selected_features_rfe)
set_importance = set(selected_features_importance)
set_scatterplot = set(selected_features_scatterplot)

# Find common features
common_features = set_univariate.intersection(set_rfe, set_importance,set_scatterplot)

# Print common features
print("Common features selected by all methods:")
for i in common_features:
    print(i)

Common features selected by all methods:

euribor3m
